Title: In utero exposure to Ramadan and Birth Outcomes: Evidence from a triple difference approach
Abstract: This study investigates the impact of fetal exposure to Ramadan fasting on birth outcomes using a triple difference methodology. Drawing on Iranian birth registry data, the paper finds that in utero exposure to Ramadan is associated with lower birth weights and shorter gestational periods, particularly among rural and low-income populations. The findings have implications for maternal health policy in Muslim-majority countries.
Classification-JEL: I15, J13, C21.
Keywords: Ramadan, birth outcomes, maternal health, triple difference, Iran.
